'''Mormon studies''' is the [[interdisciplinarity|interdisciplinary]] [[list of academic disciplines|academic]] study of the [[beliefs and practices of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints|beliefs, practices]], [[Latter Day Saint movement#History|history]] and [[Culture of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints|culture]] of those known by the term ''[[Mormon]]'' and [[list of sects in the Latter Day Saint movement|denominations]] belonging to the [[Latter Day Saint movement]] whose members do not generally go by the term "Mormon". The Latter Day Saint movement includes not only [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] (LDS Church) but also the [[Community of Christ]] (CoC) and other groups, as well as those falling under the umbrella of [[Mormon fundamentalism]].

Before 1903, writings about Mormons were mostly orthodox documentary histories or [[Anti-Mormonism|anti-Mormon]] material. The first dissertations on Mormons, published in the 1900s, had a naturalistic style that approached [[History of the Latter Day Saint movement|Mormon history]] from economic, psychological, and philosophical theories. While their position within Mormon studies is debated, Mormon [[apologetics]] have a tradition dating back to [[Parley P. Pratt]]'s response to an anti-Mormon book in 1838.

The amount of scholarship in Mormon studies increased after World War II. From 1972–1982, while [[Leonard J. Arrington|Leonard Arrington]] was a [[Church Historian and Recorder|Church Historian]] in the history department, the [[Church History Library|LDS Church Archives]] were open to Mormon and non-Mormon researchers. Researchers wrote detached accounts for Mormon intellectuals in the "New Mormon history" style. Many new publications started to publish history in this style, including [[Dialogue: A Journal of Mormon Thought|''Dialogue: A Journal of Mormon Thought'']], ''[[BYU Studies Quarterly]]'', and ''[[Woman's Exponent|Exponent II]]''. Some [[General authority|general authorities]] in the church did not like the New Mormon history style, and Arrington and his remaining staff were transferred to [[Brigham Young University]] (BYU) in 1982, where they worked in the [[Joseph Fielding Smith Institute for Church History]]. The institute continued to support scholarship in Mormon history until 2005, when the institute closed and employees transferred to the LDS Church Office Building. In the late 1980s and 1990s, several other incidents made BYU faculty reluctant to voice unorthodox ideas about church history. Around 1990, BYU professors were asked not to contribute to ''Dialogue'' or ''[[Sunstone (magazine)|Sunstone]]''. Two historians were [[Excommunication#The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints|excommunicated]] in 1993, probably for their published unorthodox views. ''BYU Studies'' and other LDS church-sponsored publishers published more "faithful" scholarship at this time. Presses outside of Utah started to publish more books in Mormon studies. 

Mormon scholars engaging in Mormon studies still feel they must be careful about what they write, especially if they work with material from the Church History Library archives. Non-Mormon scholars are often suspicious of Mormon scholars' work. This is gradually changing as Mormon scholars find employment outside of church-sponsored institutions. Universities without affiliation to the LDS Church have endowed chairs for Mormon studies. Emerging trends in "Newer" Mormon History are an increase in interdisciplinary work and women's history. The LDS Church History Department hired a women's history specialist in 2011 and has recently published books focusing on women's history. Blogs focusing on Mormon history have helped make Mormon history more accessible and provided a safe space for unorthodox ideas, although they may be superficial at times. 

==Pre-1903 writings about Mormons==
Before World War II, church histories were mostly either orthodox Mormon or anti-Mormon and written by faithful Mormons or hostile non-Mormons, respectively.{{sfn|Shipps|2007|p=504}} A few writers in the first era of church history (1830–1905) wrote about Mormons as a curiosity and focused on their peculiar ways.{{sfn|Arrington|1966|p=16}}

===Anti-Mormon literature===
Non-Mormons wrote for a non-Mormon public about how "primitive and dangerous" Mormons were in "extreme terms."{{sfn|Bushman|2013a|pp=199–200}}  [[Eber D. Howe]] published ''[[Mormonism Unvailed|Mormonism Unvailed, or a Faithful Account of that Singular Imposition and Delusion]]'' in 1834, which claimed that [[Sidney Rigdon]] was the original author of the [[Book of Mormon]] and that [[Joseph Smith]] was a "vile wretch." Howe included affidavits from people who knew Joseph Smith collected by ex-Mormon [[Doctor Philastus Hurlbut|Philastus Hurlbut]].{{sfn|Helfrich|2011|pp=53–54}} The book influenced future anti-Mormon literature. (by La Roy Sunderland, [[John C. Bennett|John Bennett]], and John A. Clark).{{sfn|Helfrich|2011|p=55}} Origen Bacheler examined the Book of Mormon itself in ''Mormonism Exposed Internally and Externally'', arguing that the book was inconsistent with the Bible and was written by Joseph Smith himself.{{sfn|Helfrich|2011|pp=56–57}}

In the 1960s, ex-Mormons [[Jerald and Sandra Tanner]] continued that anti-Mormon tradition by reprinting anti-Mormon works in the [[public domain]] as well as important but unflattering documents from LDS history through Utah Light House Ministry. They published their own criticisms of the LDS church as well, which, unlike early anti-Mormon works, cite historical documents.{{sfn|Helfrich|2011|pp=60–62}} [[Ed Decker]], an excommunicated Mormon, made two anti-Mormon films: ''[[The God Makers]]'' (1982) and ''[[The God Makers II]]'' (1993). The films described Mormons as being a [[cult]], abusing women and children, manipulating news outlets, and practicing [[Satanism]]. ''The God Makers II'' received criticism from other anti-Mormons, including Jerald and Sandra Tanner, who stated it contained inaccuracies.{{sfn|Helfrich|2011|pp=62–63}}

===Official church records and early histories===
[[File:Andrew Jenson.jpg|thumb|Andrew Jenson wrote the LDS Biographical Encyclopedia]]
Official recorders have existed since Joseph Smith organized the [[Church of Christ (Latter Day Saints)|Church of Christ]] on April 6, 1830. Church records continue to the present and are kept in the LDS church archives. The first official church history was published in 1842, when Smith and his associates began writing ''[[History of the Church (Joseph Smith)|History of Joseph Smith]]'' as an official diary of Joseph Smith. This history was published in [[Times and Seasons]] in [[Nauvoo, Illinois|Nauvoo]], and then in [[Deseret News]] and Latter-day Saints' [[Millennial Star]] up until 1863. ''History of Joseph Smith'' was followed by ''History of Brigham Young'', which was also published in Deseret News and Millennial Star over the next two years. Church Historians and their assistants edited the material, which was published in official publications.{{sfn|Arrington|1992|pp=1–2}} [[Andrew Jenson]] made sizable contributions to documentary church history with the [[Latter-day Saint Biographical Encyclopedia]] (1901–36), Encyclopedic History of the Church (1941), and an unpublished "Journal History of the Church" containing over 1,500 scrapbooks filled with published and unpublished records of daily activities in the church.{{sfn|Arrington|1992|pp=1–2}} Jenson made a special report on the [[Mountain Meadows Massacre]], and parts of the report were not openly used until [[Massacre at Mountain Meadows|''Massacre at Mountain Meadows'']] (2008) by [[Richard E. Turley Jr.|Richard E. Turley]], [[Ronald W. Walker]], and [[Glen M. Leonard]].{{sfn|Walker|2008|p=25}}

The first historian to attempt to summarize Mormon history on a large scale was [[Edward Tullidge]], who wrote ''Life of Brigham Young: or Utah and Her Founders'' (1876), ''History of Salt Lake City'' (1886), and History of Northern Utah and Southern Idaho (1889). [[Hubert Howe Bancroft|Hubert How Bancroft]] wrote ''History of Utah'' (1889) with the help of the Historian's Office.{{sfn|Arrington|1992|p=3}} Bancroft's history of Utah portrayed Mormons favorably. Critics say that he wasn't objective since he allowed LDS Church authorities to read the book before publication. Perhaps his favorable treatment was how he obtained access to the church records.{{sfn|Helfrich|2011|pp=144–145}} Expanding on Bancroft's history, [[Orson F. Whitney]] wrote ''History of Utah'' (1898–1904) in four volumes. [[Joseph Fielding Smith]] wrote ''Essentials of Church History'' in 1922. Most of these accounts combined various testimonies into a single narrative without questioning the validity of the eyewitnesses or other observers, especially those of church authorities.{{sfn|Arrington|1992|p=3}}

Mormons wrote accounts for other Mormons, often published in church-sponsored venues like ''[[Juvenile Instructor|The Juvenile Instructor]]'' and in church-published lesson manuals. These writings were written for a Mormon audience in order to support their existing beliefs. [[B. H. Roberts|Brigham H. Roberts]] was an associate editor of the ''Salt Lake Herald'' and while on a mission to England, was the editor of the ''[[Millennial Star|Millenial Star]]''. Upon returning to Utah, he became a [[General Authority]]. After an invitation from ''Americana'', Brigham H. Roberts wrote a chapter each month from 1909 to 1915 in what later became the ''[[Comprehensive History of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints|Comprehensive History of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]]: Century One''.{{sfn|Bushman|2013a|pp=199–200}} The history had some of the first historical analysis of events in church history.{{sfn|Helfrich|2011|p=140}} It was serialized in Americana 1909–1915.{{sfn|Arrington|1992|p=3}} 

From 1830-1930, women were victims or symbols in historical accounts.{{sfn|Erekson|2017|p=1}} Church historians mentioned their suffering, but rarely mentioned them by name. Anti-polygamy tracts also described Mormon women in general terms, describing them as deluded or miserable.{{sfn|Erekson|2017|p=2}} In an effort to combat the way anti-polygamists portrayed Mormon women, Edward Tullidge and Eliza R. Snow compiled ''The Women of Mormondom'' (1877), a book that portrayed Mormon women as hardworking and independent in a combined history, biography, and theology. ''Heroines of Mormondom'' (1884) highlighted faithful Mormon women's lives. Women wrote short biographies of other women and recorded them in [[Woman's Exponent|''Women's Exponent'']] and through publications from the [[Daughters of the Utah Pioneers]].{{sfn|Erekson|2017|pp=3–4}}

==Early Mormon studies==
[[File:Great Basin Desert 3 by Earth's beauty site.jpg|thumb|Great Basin Desert]]
Early academic writers on Mormon topics had a "naturalistic" approach to history, using theory from economics, psychology, and philosophy to guide their study.{{sfn|Helfrich|2011|p=155}} Richard Ely contributed to the professionalization of Mormon studies with his early dissertation "Economic Aspects of Mormonism" (1903). In the work, he praised Mormon irrigation and communalism as a good model of economic development.{{sfn|Helfrich|2011|pp=146–147}} He influenced [[Leonard J. Arrington|Leonard Arrington']]<nowiki/>s interest in economics and Mormons.{{sfn|Helfrich|2011|p=160}} Andrew Love Neff wrote "The Mormon Migration to Utah," which he finished in 1918 but had started over ten years earlier. He was interested in how Mormons helped colonize the West.{{sfn|Arrington|1966|p=19}} Mormon [[E. E. Ericksen|Ephraim Edward Ericksen]] wrote "The Psychological and Ethical Aspects of Mormonism" (1922) while studying at the University of Chicago. His dissertation, influenced by functionalist theory, argued that Mormonism was a product of conflicts with non-Mormons and harsh environments.{{sfn|Helfrich|2011|pp=147–148}} Lowry Nelson, also a Mormon, studied at the University of Wisconsin in the 1920s. He worked in agriculture and was dean of BYU's College of Applied Science and director of the Utah Agriculture Experiment stations. He wrote articles about how the Mormon village was designed to promote unity and sociability, which allowed Mormon settlers to colonize the Great Basin Desert. He left Utah in 1937.{{sfn|Helfrich|2011|pp=149–150}} [[Nels Anderson]] studied at the University of Chicago, and studied hobos in Utah, where he converted to Mormonism. His book ''Desert Saints'' (1944) recounted the history of saints in the St. George, Utah area.{{sfn|Helfrich|2011|pp=150–151}} Other scholars publishing on Mormonism from this time period include I. Woodbridge Riley, [[Walter Franklin Prince|Walter F. Prince]], Franklin D. Daines, Hamilton Gardner, Joseph Geddes, [[Feramorz Y. Fox|Feramorz Fox]], Arden Beal Olsen, William McNiff, [[Kimball Young]], [[Austin E. and Alta S. Fife|Austin Fife and Alta Fife]].{{sfn|Helfrich|2011|pp=151–154}}

In the 1950s after World War II, an increasing number of Mormons studied history professionally and wrote dissertations about Mormon history. Non-Mormon sociologist Thomas F. O'Dea wrote a dissertation entitled "Mormon Values: The Significance of a Religious Outlook for Social Action" after living in a rural Mormon farming village in New Mexico for six months and subsequently teaching at Utah State University.{{sfn|Arrington|1966|p=22}} This study of Mormon culture "stunned Mormon readers with its objectivity and sympathetic insight," according to Mormon scholar [[Richard Bushman]].{{sfn|Bushman|2013a|p=203}} [[Bernard DeVoto]], [[Dale Morgan|Dale L. Morgan]], [[Fawn M. Brodie|Fawn McKay Brodie]], Stuart Ferguson, and [[Juanita Brooks]] did not have graduate degrees in history, but made significant contributions to the foundations of Mormonism's "New History" movement.{{sfn|Shipps|2007|pp=499–500}}{{sfn|Helfrich|2011|pp=151–154}} Brodie wrote [[No Man Knows My History|''No Man Knows My History'']] (1945), which contemporary reviews praised as definitive and scholarly. Other LDS scholars, notably [[Hugh Nibley]], criticized Brodie's biography.{{sfn|Shipps|2007|pp=499–500}} In 1950, Juanita Brooks, an educated Mormon housewife, published a scholarly book on the Mountain Meadows Massacre, which is well-researched and balanced even by contemporary standards. Brooks's Mormon neighbors did not like "the frankness" of her book.{{sfn|Bushman|2013a|p=202}}

==Apologetics and polemics==
{{anchor|Apologetics}}
<!--Please don't edit text within above anchor template. Thanks.-->
{{see also|Apologetics#Mormonism|Criticism of Mormonism}}

Mormon scholars are divided on whether apologetics should be considered part of Mormon studies or not. Brian D. Birch argues that it should be a part of Mormon studies, as long as apologetic authors concede that their arguments are objective and subject to academic debate.{{sfn|Birch|2014}} Apologists write defensively, and view their polemical responses to criticism as a battle for their faith.{{sfn|Bushman|2007|pp=518–519}} [[Parley P. Pratt]] responded to ''Mormonism Unveiled'' in detail in his 1838 pamphlet ''Mormonism Unveiled: Zion's Watchman Unmasked and Its Editor Mr. L.R. Sunderland Exposed, Truth Vindicated, the Devil Mad, and Priestcraft in Danger!'' Pratt argued against Sunderland's character, quoting Hurlbut, who stated that Sunderland has a "notorious character."{{sfn|Helfrich|2011|p=69}}

Hugh Nibley's ''No Ma'am, That's Not History'' set a standard for apologetics to use academic language, and criticized Brodie's use of sources in her controversial biography of Joseph Smith, ''No Man Knows My History''.{{sfn|Helfrich|2011|pp=70–72}} The [[Foundation for Ancient Research and Mormon Studies]] (FARMS) aimed to support the historical authenticity of the Book of Mormon and respond to criticism, and used Nibley's style{{sfn|Helfrich|2011|pp=70–72}} to counter research that contradicted the Book of Mormon's ancient origins.{{sfn|Bushman|2007|p=517}} FARMS collaborated with [[Deseret Book Company|Deseret Book]] to publish the complete works of Hugh Nibley starting in 1984.{{sfn|Helfrich|2011|pp=70–72}} In 1997, LDS church president [[Gordon B. Hinckley]] invited FARMS to be officially affiliated at BYU, and in 2006 it was subsumed by the [[Neal A. Maxwell Institute of Religious Scholarship]].{{sfn|Helfrich|2011|pp=70–72}} In 2012, Daniel C. Petersen, the editor of ''[[FARMS Review]]'', started publishing a new journal called [[Interpreter (journal)|''Interpreter'']].<ref>{{citation|last=Peterson|first=Daniel C.|title=The Role of Apologetics in Mormon Studies|date=December 14, 2012|url=http://www.mormoninterpreter.com/the-role-of-apologetics-in-mormon-studies/|work=Mormoninterpreter.com|accessdate=2013-09-04|authorlink=Daniel C. Peterson}} — Note: this is a reprint of Peterson's August 2012 FAIR speech "Of 'Mormon Studies' and Apologetics".</ref> The [[FairMormon|Foundation for Apologetic Information and Research]] (FAIR), a group including both laypeople and academics, attempts to answer criticisms of the Mormon faith.{{sfn|Bushman|2007|p=517}} in 2013, it changed its name to [[FairMormon]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.fairmormon.org/about|title=About FairMormon – FairMormon|work=FairMormon|access-date=2018-07-25|language=en-US}}</ref> 

Some other Mormon "insiders" countered the Book of Mormon's ancient origins through the Smith-Pettit Foundation in Salt Lake City and George Smith's [[Signature Books]] publishing company. Signature Books published ''New Approaches to the Book of Mormon'' by Brent Metcalfe and ''American Apocrypha'' by Dan Vogel and Metcalfe.{{sfn|Helfrich|2011|pp=73–74}} These insider views of the Book of Mormon's origins were diverse. ''American Apocrypha'' described the Book of Mormon as a work of fiction reflecting its environment. Ostler argued that the Book of Mormon was partially inspired.{{sfn|Helfrich|2011|p=75}} FARMS's responses were at times patronizing, and even descending into veiled name-calling in William Hamblin's 1994 critique of a Metcalfe essay.{{sfn|Helfrich|2011|pp=76–77}}

===Counter-apologetics===
{{see also|Counter-apologetics}}
In the 1990s and 2000s, [[Evangelicalism|Evangelicals]] Carl Mosser and Paul Owen encouraged other Evangelicals to respond to Mormon apologetics. Evangelical [[Craig Blomberg|Craig L. Blomberg]] discussed whether or not Mormons were Christian with Mormon [[Stephen E. Robinson]] in ''How Wide the Divide? A Mormon and Evangelical in Conversation''.{{sfn|Helfrich|2011|p=79}} Richard Bushman encouraged fellow Mormon historians to be less defensive and more open to criticism, and also to do research on Mormon history from a consciously Mormon point of view.{{sfn|Bushman|2007|p=521}}

==New Mormon history==
In the 1960s, a new generation of Mormon scholars emerged. The publication of [[Dialogue: A Journal of Mormon Thought|''Dialogue: A Journal of Mormon Thought'']], the newly-established Mormon History Association, and the professionalization of LDS and RLDS history departments provided spaces for historians to do new research in Mormon topics.{{sfn|Shipps|2007|pp=498–499}} RLDS scholars founded the [[John Whitmer Historical Association]] in 1972.{{sfn|Barlow|2004}} In 1974, [[Claudia Bushman]] and [[Laurel Thatcher Ulrich]] founded the magazine ''[[Woman's Exponent|Exponent II]]''.{{sfn|Helfrich|2011|p=164}} The first issue of [[BYU Studies Quarterly|''BYU Studies'']] was published in 1959.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Arrington|first1=Leonard|title=An Economic Interpretation of the "Word of Wisdom"|journal=BYU Studies|date=1959|volume=1|issue=1|url=https://byustudies.byu.edu/content/economic-interpretation-word-wisdom|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref>

[[File:Leonard Arrington 1950s.jpeg|thumb|Leonard Arrington]]
Also in 1972, the LDS Church hired Leonard Arrington as their historian.{{sfn|Shipps|2007|p=501}} During Arrington's time as historian, Mormon and non-Mormon historians were allowed to access the [[Church History Library|LDS Church Archives]]. Much of the research in the 1970s used these newly-available sources to examine church history, sometimes in great detail.{{sfn|Shipps|2007|p=502}} Leonard Arrington influenced important scholars of Mormon history, including [[Richard L. Jensen|Richard Jensen]], [[William G. Hartley|William Hartley]], and [[Ronald W. Walker|Ronald Walker]].{{sfn|Helfrich|2011|p=164}} In 1969, Jewish historian [[Moses Rischin]] named the increasing amount of Mormon scholarship "the New Mormon history."{{sfn|Bushman|2013a|p=203}} The "New Mormon History" movement included non-Mormons Thomas F. O'Dea, P.A.M. Taylor, [[Mario De Pillis]], Lawrence Foster, Community of Christ member Robert Flanders, and Mormon scholar Klaus Hansen.{{sfn|Newell|2013|p=5}}{{sfn|Barlow|2004}} 

[[Maureen Ursenbach Beecher]] was a leading researcher in women's studies.{{sfn|Whittaker|2013}}{{sfn|Cope|2012|p=102}} In the 1970s women's biographies were published, but not integrated into larger narratives.{{sfn|Erekson|2017|p=2}} Other women hired by the Church Historical Department included Jill Mulvay Derr, Carol Cornwall Madsen, and Edyth Romney. Journals dedicated special issues to Mormon women, and the increased interest in Mormon women led to more publications focused on them. Scholars published biographies of Emma Smith, Eliza Snow, Emmeline B. Wells, and Amy Brown Lyman.{{sfn|Erekson|2017|p=5}} 

Some writers looked at Mormon women's history with the goal of restructuring historical narratives. Mormon feminist articles on Mormon history started with the special Summer 1971 issue of ''Dialogue'' on women's issues and continued in publications like ''Exponent II'' (starting in 1974), and ''Mormon Sisters: Women in Early Utah'' (1976), edited by [[Claudia Bushman]]. Beecher and Laurel Thatcher Ulrich edited another volume about Mormon women's history in ''Sisters in Sprit: Mormon Women in Historical and Cultural Perspective'' (1987). ''Women and Authority: Re-emerging Mormon Feminism'' (1992) was another milestone in feminist publications, and it encouraged Mormon women to be empowered by their history and "reclaim lost opportunities."{{sfn|Erekson|2017|p=6}}

Most New Mormon historians were LDS.{{sfn|Newell|2013|p=6}} Their audience was Mormon intellectuals{{sfn|Newell|2013|p=5}} and non-Mormons.{{sfn|Bushman|2013a|p=204}} They maintained their respect for the Mormon faith, admitted to flaws in people and policies, and avoided taking a defensive stance,{{sfn|Bushman|2013a|p=204}} a tone which non-Mormon historian [[Jan Shipps]] wrote "made them seem more secular than they actually were."{{sfn|Shipps|2007|pp=504–505}} Mormon history by non-Mormons at this time had a similar detached tone.{{sfn|Bushman|2013a|p=204}} New Mormon historians often published with the [[University of Illinois Press]] in order to publish for an academic audience independent of the church.{{sfn|Bushman|2013a|p=206}} Charles S. Peterson argued in ''The Great Basin Kingdom Revisited'' that Arrington took an exceptionalist view of Mormon history, which he then taught to other New Mormon Historians. This exceptionalist view was that they could believe in both secular history and orthodox Mormon views of the restoration.{{sfn|Helfrich|2011|pp=234–235}}

==LDS church reaffirms orthodoxy and New Mormon Faith Historians==
The LDS church stopped funding so much research and limited access to the church archives.{{sfn|Shipps|2007|p=510}} Apostle [[Ezra Taft Benson]] warned employees in the [[Church Educational System]] against New Mormon History in a 1976 speech. He said that writing history in a neutral style undermined "prophetic history."  [[Boyd K. Packer]]'s 1981 article, "The Mantle is Far, Far Greater than the Intellect" was published in ''BYU Studies.'' He wrote that contemporary historians were too eager to focus on the faults of church leaders and dismiss spiritual inspiration.{{sfn|Helfrich|2011|p=215}} In 1982, historians from Arrington's department were transferred to Brigham Young University, where they were assigned to teach in the history department and worked in the Joseph Fielding Smith Institute for Church History.{{sfn|Anderson|2005}}

[[File:Carol C. Madsen (41596667191).jpg|thumb|Carol Cornwall Madsen]]
After Arrington's death in 1999, [[Ronald K. Esplin]] and [[Jill Mulvay Derr]] led the Joseph Fielding Smith Institute for Church History at BYU. [[Carol Cornwall Madsen]] led research in the Women's History Initiative at the institute, where she wrote an important biographical study of [[Emmeline B. Wells]].{{sfn|Shipps|2007|p=512}} In 2001,{{sfn|Bushman|2009|137}} [[Richard Bushman]] retired from full-time teaching at [[Columbia University]] and was a research director at the Smith Institute.{{sfn|Shipps|2007|p=513}} [[Dean C. Jessee]] started editing Joseph Smith's papers in ''The Personal Writings of Joseph Smith''. The Smith Institute closed in 2005, and institute staff along with the Smith papers project moved to the [[Church Office Building]].{{sfn|Shipps|2007|p=512}} The [[The Joseph Smith Papers|Joseph Smith Papers]] project, started by the LDS church in 2001, aimed to publish Joseph Smith's papers with rigorous accuracy, and was validated by the National Historic Public Records Commission.{{sfn|Bushman|2013a|p=205}} 

[[Jan Shipps]] asserts that this reluctance to support new Mormon history was a response to the [[Mark Hofmann]] document forgeries. Also, some church authorities disliked the books and articles produced by the history department, which noted flaws as well as strengths of people in church history.{{sfn|Shipps|2007|p=510}} Shipps states that the increase in new converts to the LDS Church led General Authorities to emphasize the need for "palatable" versions of church history in museums and historic sites rather than in-depth articles in church-sponsored publications.{{sfn|Shipps|2007|p=511}} Mormon sociologist [[Armand Mauss]] argued that Mormonism was a struggle between remaining distinctive and assimilating to accepted American cultural practices; scholar Ronald Helfrich speculates that the change in General Authority's reception to Arrington's research was because they feared assimilating too much.{{sfn|Helfrich|2011|p=218}} General interest in Mormon studies continued during the 1980s, with over 2,000 books, articles, and other material published on Mormon history during that decade.{{sfn|Barlow|2004}} 

''BYU Studies'' and Deseret Books published more "New Mormon Faith Historians" after General Authority pushback against New Mormon History. One of these New Mormon Faith Historians was [[Louis C. Midgley|Louis Midgely]], who argued that from a relativist, postmodern theory, the Mormon view that the LDS Church had divine origins was just as valuable and valid as others. New Mormon Faith Historians said that the New Mormon scholars left faith out of their analyses.{{sfn|Helfrich|2011|pp=219–220}} Many were members of FARMS, and often saw writers of New Mormon History as the same as other anti-Mormons, even though most writers of New Mormon History were Mormon.{{sfn|Helfrich|2011|p=221–222}} The difference between the New Mormon Faith Historians and New Mormon scholars was hard to define.{{sfn|Helfrich|2011|pp=219–220}} 

Along with Arrington's transfer and a subsequent increase in restrictions in the LDS Church Archives, several other incidents led to an intellectual chilling of Mormon history by Mormons in the 1990s.{{sfn|Schuessler|2012}} In 1992, Arrington wrote that "the church cannot afford to place its official stamp of approval on any 'private' interpretation of its past," and this kind of history must be not sponsored by the LDS Church.{{sfn|Arrington|1992|pp=4–5}} In September 1993, the LDS church excommunicated the [[September Six]], which included two historians: [[Lavina Fielding Anderson]] and [[D. Michael Quinn]]. These excommunications served as a warning to other Mormon historians.{{sfn|Shipps|2007|p=510}} Quinn's excommunication was perhaps tied to his idea that Mormon women had been given the priesthood in 1843, which he published in an essay in ''Women and Authority: Re-emerging Mormon Feminism''.{{sfn|Helfrich|2011|pp=224–225}} In 2003, he was scheduled to give a speech at a conference at Yale which was co-sponsored by BYU, and BYU stated they would withdraw their funding if Quinn presented his paper. That same year, Quinn applied to work as a professor at the University of Utah and Arizona State University. He was not hired as a professor, possibly because of fears that LDS people in power would retaliate against the university.{{sfn|Helfrich|2011|pp=227–228}} In 1986, administrators were asked not to contribute to ''Dialogue'' or present at the [[Sunstone (magazine)|Sunstone]] symposium; around 1990, BYU professors were asked not to contribute to ''Dialogue'' or ''Sunstone''.{{sfn|Hansen|2010|pp=40–41}} [[Eugene England]], one of the founders of ''Dialogue'' and then a professor at BYU, spoke out against these prohibitions. He was asked not to write for the ''Encyclopedia of Mormonism'' in 1990, and in 1998 he was asked to retire from BYU without justification. England saw this as stemming from his publicly anti-war stance, and for his attention to Mormon racism and sexism. He viewed his differences as a potential source of learning for himself and others. After retiring from BYU, he started one of the first Mormon studies programs at [[Utah Valley University|Utah Valley State College]]. According to a 1997 report by the [[American Association of University Professors]] on academic freedom at BYU, Alan Wilkins was questioned about his motives for contributing to ''Dialogue'' and ''Sunstone'' in a tenure review. The report also mentioned other incidents where BYU administration criticized speakers and articles for criticism of the church, among other complaints.{{sfn|Pratt|1997|p=63}} 

In 1997, [[Joanna Brooks]] argued that the goal of Mormon studies was to critically examine Mormonism, not to determine religious truths.{{sfn|Brooks|1997|p=135}} She postulated that Mormon studies done as a type of cultural studies will help scholars in the field feel less defensive and more productive.{{sfn|Brooks|1997|p=138}} Outside of Brigham Young University and Utah, the [[University of North Carolina Press]], [[Alfred A. Knopf|Knopf]], and the [[University of Oklahoma Press]] published books on Mormonism.{{sfn|Barlow|2004}} In the 2000s, Jan Shipps was a large influence on news articles about Mormons; often she is the only expert cited for an entire article.{{sfn|Barlow|2004}} In 2005, the National Endowment for the Humanities held a seminar at Brigham Young University on the bicentennial of Joseph Smith's birth.{{sfn|Bushman|2013a|p=197}}  [[Terryl Givens]], a comparative literature scholar, analyzed discourse about the Book of Mormon in ''By the Hand of Mormon: The American Scripture that Launched a New World Religion'' in 2002. {{sfn|McLemee|2002}}

Mormon women's history has not been well-integrated in general histories. Arrington and Davis Bitton discussed women's issues in two chapters on marriage and sisterhood in ''The Mormon Experience'' (1992). ''The Story of the Latter-day Saints'' (1992) by James Allen and Glen Leonard mentioned women in the context of auxiliaries like Relief Society and Primary, plural marriage, suffrage, and the ERA. ''The Encyclopedia of Latter-day Saint History'' (2000) contained 435 entries about men, but only 64 about women, with three-quarters of the women receiving less than a page of description. Church publication ''Our Heritage'' (1996) only mentioned a few women. Women's history remained in a "separate sphere."{{sfn|Erekson|2017|p=7–8}} ''Daughters in My Kingdom'' (2011), an official history of the Relief Society, is mostly used in women's meetings. Outside of Mormon history specialists, Mormon women are rarely mentioned.{{sfn|Erekson|2017|p=9}}

==Newer Mormon history==
Non-Mormon scholars are still often suspicious of LDS scholars' work.{{sfn|Newell|2013|p=3}} That is gradually changing as non-Mormon scholars increase and universities not affiliated with the LDS Church have endowed chairs for Mormon studies.{{sfn|Newell|2013|p=4}} [[Kathleen Flake]] is the first Richard L. Bushman Chair of Mormon Studies at [[University of Virginia]], and [[Patrick Q. Mason|Patrick Mason]] is the Howard W. Hunter Chair of Mormon Studies at Claremont Graduate University in California.{{sfn|Walker|2013}}

[[File:Church History Library in Salt Lake City.jpg|thumb|Church History Library in Salt Lake City]]
The Church History Library still restricts access to certain documents for most scholars. Scholars may self-censor their research for fear of losing access to documents from the Church History Library. Previous excommunications of Mormon historians give Mormon researchers the sense that they are being watched.{{sfn|Newell|2013|p=4}} Scholars from various disciplines see the "New Mormon History" movement as ending, bring replaced by "Post New Mormon History" or "Newer Mormon History." This emerging movement is interdisciplinary and endeavors to place Mormon studies in a broader historical context, further eroding boundaries between disciplines.{{sfn|Newell|2013|pp=6–7}} Mormon women's history has not been well-integrated with other Mormon studies topics.{{sfn|Coles|2018}} Contemporary historians like [[R. Marie Griffith]], [[Grant Wacker]], and [[Robert Orsi]] encourage the use of interdisciplinary tools in Mormon studies.{{sfn|Cope|2012|p=100}}

Included in these interdisciplinary tools are oral histories. In 1972, an the Charles Redd Center for Western Studies was established at BYU, where Jessie L. Embry directed an extensive oral history project.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Murphy |first1=John |last2=Ainsworth |first2=GlendaLynn |last3=Casper |first3=Zann |last4=Balif |first4=Elizabeth |title=Charles Redd Center for Western Studies oral history project records|url=https://findingaid.lib.byu.edu/viewItem/MSS%207752 |website=findingaid.lib.byu.edu |publisher=L. Tom Perry Special Collections |accessdate=30 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Ainsworth |first1=GlendaLynn |last2=Murphy |first2=John |title=Jessie L. Embry papers |url=https://findingaid.lib.byu.edu/viewItem/MSS%203211 |website=findingaid.lib.byu.edu |publisher=L. Tom Perry Special Collections |accessdate=30 July 2018}}</ref> The Church History Department started their own oral history project in 2009.{{sfn|Erekson|2017|p=6}} Claudia L. Bushman and her students started the Claremont Oral History collection in 2009, and papers using the oral history data were published in ''Mormon Women Have Their Say: Essays from the Claremont Oral History Collection''.{{sfn|Bushman|Kline|2013b}}

The LDS Church History Department hired a specialist in women's history in 2011, Kate Holbrook. She co-authored ''The First Fifty Years of Relief Society: Key Documents in Latter-Day Saint Women's History'' with Jill Mulvay Derr, Carol Cornwall Madsen, and Matthew J. Grow. Laurel Thatcher Ulrich said the book was "the most important work to emerge from a Mormon Press in the last 50 years." Jenny Reeder, specializing in 19th century women's history, was hired in 2013. Brittany Chapman Nash and Lisa Tait also specialize in women's history and work in the LDS Church history department. Nash works in public services and helps researchers to be aware of women's sources the archive offers. She co-authored ''Women of Faith in the Latter Days'' with [[Richard E. Turley Jr.|Richard Turley]]. Tait works on the web team, helping to add a "Women of Conviction" section to church history website.{{sfn|Walch|2016}} In 2017, Reeder and Holbrook edited a compilation of women's speeches called ''At the Pulpit: 185 Years of Discourses by Latter-day Saint Women.'' {{sfn|Walch|2017}}

==Blogs and Mormon studies==
The [[Mormon blogosphere]] influences Mormon studies. In 2011, Patrick Mason surveyed 113 Mormon blog readers who were also graduate students.{{sfn|Mason|2012|p=13}} Most respondents viewed blogs as a way to democratize Mormon studies. Since blogs are independent from Church institutions, many felt that blogs were a safe space to test more unorthodox ideas.{{sfn|Mason|2012|p=17}} A few observed that men's voices are more prominent in the blogging community, though a few prominent blogs have all-women authors.{{sfn|Mason|2012|p=18}} Other respondents felt that blogs made Mormon studies "more of an echo chamber," and were "superficial," and "glorified navel-gazing."{{sfn|Mason|2012|pp=18–19}}  One of the most popular blogs, By Common Consent, had over two million page visitors in 2011. It and other blogs are influential on Mormon studies.{{sfn|Mason|2012|p=20}}

== Archives ==
Archives with significant Mormon collections include the [[L. Tom Perry Special Collections]] at BYU, the Church Archives in Salt Lake, the J. Willard Marriott Library at the [[University of Utah]] in Salt Lake, Utah State University Libraries, and the Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript Library at Yale in New Haven, Connecticut.{{sfn|Helfrich|2011|p=165}}

== Awards ==
Awards for writing or service in the field of Mormon studies are presented annually by scholarly societies.  The [[Mormon History Association]] (MHA) and the [[John Whitmer Historical Association]] (JWHA) each present annual awards for various categories within Mormon history, such as books, biographies, documentary history, journal articles, and lifetime achievement.<ref name=mha_awards>{{cite web | title=MHA Awards | work=mormonhistoryassociation.org | publisher=Mormon History Association | url=https://www.mormonhistoryassociation.org/awards | accessdate=2015-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Awards | work=jwha.info | publisher=John Whitmer Historical Association | url=http://www.jwha.info/awards | accessdate=2015-01-26}}</ref>   The MHA also gives awards for theses and student papers.<ref name=mha_awards/>  The [[Utah State Historical Society]] (USHS), which frequently engages Mormon history, also presents awards for books, articles, and student papers.<ref>{{cite web | title=NEWS: Utah State History Announces 2013 Annual Awards | date=September 17, 2013 | work=Utah Cultural Alliance: Unifying Utah's Cultural Community | url=http://ut-cultural-alliance.blogspot.com/2013/09/news-utah-state-history-announces-2013.html
 | accessdate=2015-01-26}}</ref> [[AML Awards|Literary awards]] are presented by the [[Association for Mormon Letters]], often awarding Mormon publications in biography, criticism, and special categories.  ''[[Dialogue: A Journal of Mormon Thought]]'' honors the best contributions to its journal<ref>{{cite web | title=Dialogue’s Best of 2011 Awards | date=June 1, 2012 | work=dialoguejournal.com | publisher=Dialogue Foundation | url=https://www.dialoguejournal.com/2012/dialogues-best-of-2011-awards/ | accessdate=2015-01-26}}</ref> and ''[[Interpreter: A Journal of Mormon Scripture]]'' awards the best article submitted by a woman.<ref>{{cite web | title=The Ruth M. Stephens Article Prize | work=mormoninterpreter.com | publisher=Interpreter: A Journal of Mormon Scripture | url=http://www.mormoninterpreter.com/the-ruth-m-stephens-article-prize/ | accessdate=2015-01-26}}</ref>

Universities also present awards.  The [[University of Utah]] gives the Juanita Brooks Prize in Mormon Studies<ref>{{cite news | author=Brian Passey | title=New book collects Juanita Brooks Lectures | date=November 22, 2014 | work=The Spectrum | url=http://www.thespectrum.com/story/life/faith/2014/11/22/new-book-collects-juanita-brooks-lectures/19425943/ | accessdate=2015-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Juanita Brooks Prize in Mormon Studies | work=The University of Utah Press | publisher=J. Willard Marriott Library, The University of Utah | url=http://www.uofupress.com/juanita-brooks-prize.php | accessdate=2015-01-26}}</ref> and offers a Mormon Studies Fellowship.<ref>{{cite web | title=Humanities Fellowships: Mormon Studies Fellowship | work=Tanner Humanities Center | publisher=College of Humanities, University of Utah | url=http://thc.utah.edu/fellowships/mormon-studies.php | accessdate=2015-01-26}}</ref> [[Utah State University]]'s Evans Biography Awards focus on biographies significant to "[[Mormon corridor|Mormon Country]]".<ref>{{cite web | title=Evans Biography Awards | work=Mountain West Center for Regional Studies | publisher=Utah State University | url=http://mountainwest.usu.edu/evans.aspx | accessdate=2015-01-26}}</ref>  Student writing competitions are held by Utah State University,<ref>{{cite web | title=Arrington Writing Awards Open to Utah College Students | date=September 11, 2014 | work=Utah State Today | publisher=Utah State University | url=http://www.usu.edu/ust/index.cfm?article=54088 | accessdate=2015-01-26}}</ref> the MHA,<ref name=mha_awards/> and the JWHA.<ref>{{cite web | title=Scholarships | work=jwha.info | publisher=John Whitmer Historical Association | url=http://www.jwha.info/scholarships | accessdate=2015-01-26}}</ref> [[BYU Religious Education]] presents annual awards to its faculty for teaching, research, and service, as well as books in the categories of church history or ancient scripture.<ref>{{cite journal | title=Faculty and Staff | journal=[[BYU Religious Education Review]] | date=Fall 2013 | page=29 | url=http://rsc.byu.edu/review/fall-2013 | accessdate=2015-01-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | title=Faculty and Staff | journal=[[BYU Religious Education Review]] | date=Fall 2014 | page=29 | url=http://rsc.byu.edu/review/fall-2014 | accessdate=2015-01-29}}</ref>

== Academic programs ==
Several universities have programs in the study of Mormonism, with professors named to oversee coursework, research, and events on Mormon studies.  While independent academic programs have emerged in recent years, devotional religious education programs have existed far longer.  Additional colleges have also taught courses on Mormonism without having institutionally sponsored programs,<ref>{{cite web | title=New Series: Mormon Studies in the Classroom | author=Benjamin Park | date=April 21, 2014 | work=Juvenile Instructor | url=http://juvenileinstructor.org/new-series-mormon-studies-in-the-classroom/ | accessdate=2017-12-12}}</ref> but they are not included in the list below.

=== Independent ===
* [[Utah State University]], Program of Religious Studies, including the Arrington Chair of Mormon History and Culture (est. 2007)
* [[Claremont Graduate University]], School of Religion, including the Hunter Chair of Mormon Studies (est. 2008)<ref>{{citation |publisher= [[Deseret News]] |url= http://www.deseretnews.com/article/865550124/California-graduate-university-takes-academic-approach-to-Mormonism.html |title= California graduate university takes academic approach to Mormonism |first= Rachel |last= Brutsch |date= February 15, 2012}}</ref>
* [[Utah Valley University]], Comparative Mormon Studies program<ref>{{cite web | title=Comparative Mormon Studies | publisher=Utah Valley University | url=https://www.uvu.edu/religiousstudies/mormon_studies/mormon_studies.html | accessdate=2017-12-12}}</ref>
* [[University of Utah]], Tanner Humanities Center's Mormon Studies Initiative,<ref>{{cite web | title=Mormon Studies Initiative – Keeping Our Shoulder to the Wheel | work=Tanner Humanities Center | publisher=The University of Utah | url=http://thc.utah.edu/lectures-programs/MormonStudies.php | accessdate=2015-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Religion Studies Program Helps Students Gain Understanding | author=Tyler Olsen | date=September 30, 2014 | work=[[The Daily Utah Chronicle]] | url=http://www.dailyutahchronicle.com/2014/09/30/religion-studies-program-helps-students-gain-understanding/ | accessdate=2015-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | author=Benjamin Wood | title=University of Utah to offer course in literary qualities of Book of Mormon | date=August 14, 2013 | work=[[Deseret News]] | url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/865584673/University-of-Utah-to-offer-course-on-literary-qualities-of-Book-of-Mormon.html?pg=all | accessdate=2015-01-26}}</ref> including the Marlin K. Jensen Scholar and Artist in Residence (est. 2016)<ref>{{cite news | author=Peggy Fletcher Stack | title=U. establishes fellowship in honor of popular emeritus Mormon leader Marlin Jensen | date=January 19, 2016 | work=Salt Lake Tribune | url=http://archive.sltrib.com/article.php?id=3437415&itype=CMSID | accessdate=2018-01-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | author=Tad Walch | title=The LDS Church and the growing Mormon Studies field | date=December 9, 2016 | work=Deseret News | url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/865668926/The-LDS-Church-and-the-growing-Mormon-Studies-field.html | accessdate=2018-01-29}}</ref> and the Simmons Professor of Mormon Studies (est. 2017)<ref>{{cite news | title=The University of Utah’s first Mormon Studies professor is a historian researching early black converts | author=Bob Mims | date=September 20, 2017 | work=Salt Lake Tribune | url=http://www.sltrib.com/news/2017/09/20/u-prof-reeve-named-first-simmons-mormon-studies-professor/ | accessdate=2017-12-12}}</ref>
* [[University of Virginia]], Graduate Program in Religious Studies, including the Richard Lyman Bushman Chair of Mormon Studies (est. 2012)<ref>{{citation |author= [[Peggy Fletcher Stack]] |url= http://www.sltrib.com/sltrib/blogsfaithblog/55085181-180/mormon-studies-chair-university.html.csp |title= U. of Virginia’s Bushman honor gives Mormon studies another boost |series= Following Faith |newspaper= The Salt Lake Tribune |date= October 15, 2012 |accessdate=2013-10-30}}</ref>
* [[University of Wyoming]], Mormon Studies Initiative <ref>{{cite news | title=Mormon Studies starts at University of Wyo. | author=Shauna Stephenson | date=March 1, 2007 | work=WyomingNews.com | publisher=WyomingTribuneEagle | url=https://www.wyomingnews.com/news/mormon-studies-starts-at-university-of-wyo/article_12dee12b-f52e-59bc-aefc-eda3e1cecddc.html | accessdate=2017-12-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=LDS Church gifts $1 million to Mormon studies at USU just as professor moves to BYU for a year | author=Tad Walch | date=December 14, 2016 | work=Deseret News | url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/865669293/LDS-Church-gifts-1-million-to-Mormon-studies-at-USU-just-as-professor-moves-to-BYU-for-a-year.html | accessdate=2017-12-12}}</ref>
* [[University of Southern California]], School of Religion, including the John A. Widtsoe Chair of Mormon Studies (announced 2015)<ref>{{cite news | author=Gerry Avant | title=President Uchtdorf speaks at inaugural John A. Widtsoe Symposium at USC | work=[[LDS Church News]] | date=May 1, 2015 | url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/865627281/USC-hosts-symposium-for-Mormon-apostle.html?pg=all | accessdate=2015-05-30}}</ref>
* [[Graduate Theological Union]], Director of Mormon Studies (named 2017)<ref>{{cite web | title=Robert A. Rees Named Director of Mormon Studies | date=March 17, 2017 | work=GTU News| publisher=Graduate Theological Union | url=https://www.gtu.edu/news/robert-rees-named-director-mormon-studies | accessdate=2017-12-12}}</ref>

=== Denominationally affiliated ===
{{see also|Academic freedom at Brigham Young University}}
* [[Brigham Young University]] Religious Education (Provo, Utah; [[Brigham Young University–Idaho|Rexburg, Idaho]]; [[Brigham Young University–Hawaii|Laie, Hawaii campus]]es; and also the [[BYU Jerusalem Center|BYU Jerusalem Center for Near Eastern Studies]]) — For official LDS Church approved religious instruction.
** Advanced historical research is instead conducted at the LDS Church's [[Church History Library]], while BYU's [[Harold B. Lee Library]] and the [[Huntington Library]] also hold historical materials important to Mormon studies.
* [[Fuller Theological Seminary#School of Intercultural Studies|Fuller Theological Seminary's School of Intercultural Studies]] — Department at multi-denominational Protestant Christian seminary that has occasionally held seminars on Evangelical–Latter-day Saint dialogue and comparative theology <ref>{{cite journal | author=[[Craig L. Blomberg]] | title=Mormon-Evangelical Dialogue | journal=[[Religious Educator]] | volume=13 | issue=1 | date=2012 | url=http://rsc.byu.edu/archived/volume-13-number-1-2012/mormon-evangelical-dialogue | accessdate=2015-02-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | author=[[Robert L. Millet]] | title=The Mormon-Evangelical Dialogue | journal=Evangelical Interfaith Dialogue | date=Fall 2012 | url=http://cms.fuller.edu/EIFD/issues/Fall_2012/The_Mormon_Evangelical_Dialogue.aspx | accessdate=2015-02-02}}</ref>
* [[Graceland University]] — [[Non-denominational]] university affiliated with the [[Community of Christ]]. Teaches religion classes and is connected with the denomination's seminary.
* LDS Church [[Institute of Religion|Institutes of Religion]] — Offers official LDS Church approved religious instruction, often at locations adjacent to institutions of higher learning

